ownedComment.body: Author:s.dana. Created:1/10/14 10:02 AM. Title:. Comment:.
The root class/element; attributes pertain to the status and format of the report and when generated.
Identifies the time that the election report was generated.
Format of the results, e.g., contest summary, precinct level results, etc.
Indicates whether this file is part of a sequence of files.
Indicates the upper bound of the sequence.
Status of the election report, e.g., test mode, unofficial, etc.
An identifier of the vendor application generating the election report, e.g., X-EMS version 3.1.a.
Class/element for associating a ballot style with a reporting unit, e.g., a precinct.

Class/element for describing a geo-politically bounded area of geography such as a city, district, or jurisdiction, or a precinct or split-precinct, or specific vote-capture device, for the purpose of associating contest vote counts and ballot counts (and other information) with the reporting unit. Reporting units can link to each other to form a hierarchicallly-oriented model of a state's (or a county's, etc.) jurisdictions, districts, and precincts.
Name of the reporting unit.
Abstract class /element for a contest. Classes/elements for specific types of contests inherit the attributes and define their own.
For associating a contest with its corresponding district, e.g., a ReportingUnit class/element of type=district, thereby identifying the scope of the contest.
Title or name of the contest, e.g., "Governor" or "Question on Legalization of Gambling".
Defines the sequence in which this Contest appears when displaying results.
Number of precincts that have completed reporting votes for this contest.
Total number of precincts that have this contest on the ballot.
Vote variation associated with the contest, e.g., n-of-m, etc.
Class/element for describing information about a candidate in a contest.
Candidate's name as listed on the ballot.
Registration status of the candidate, e.g., filed, qualified, etc.
Class/element for describing information about a political party. Can also be a type of ballot selection for tracking a count of straight party selections.
Short name for the party, e.g., "DEM".
Official full name of the party, e.g., "Republican".
This class is used to identify and report on information regarding various types of localities, including jurisdictions and districts down to precincts and ultimately devices.

Class/element for type of contest involving ballot measures (i.e.,referenda). Inherits attributes from the Contest class/element; includes other attributes for including text from the ballot measure if available.
The full text of the referendum.
The summary text of the referendum.

Class/element for type of contest involving one or more candCodeates. Inherits attributes from the Contest class/element; includes other attributes to indicate number of candCodeates that are elected to the office (usually 1) and the number of votes that a voter can cast in the contest (usually 1) so as to support the n-of-m vote variation.
Number of candidates that are elected in the contest ("M" of N-of-M).
Maximum number of votes/writeins per voter in this contest ("N" of N-of-M).

class/element for reporting on contest vote counts. Contains attributes to categorize the counts according to voting classification (e.g., election day, early voting, etc.) and type of device on which the votes were cast(e.g., DRE, accessible device, etc.)

Class/element that serves as a selection for a contest, so that counts can be reported and associated with device types and voting classes. Can be for a ballot measure, candCodeate, overvote, write-in, etc.
Defines the sequence in which this BallotSelection appears within its Contest when displaying results.
Class/element that is a type of ballot selection specific to ballot measures, e.g., "yes", "no".
Enumerations for various status applicable to a candidate in Candidate, e.g., filed, winner, etc.
For ranked order voting.
Class/element describing a specific vote-capture device.
Device's serial number of other unique identifier.
Enumerations for type of device in Device and for type of device associated with vote counts in Votes.
For hand-counted paper ballots or other ballots manually counted.
Enumerations for classes of voting associated with votes in Votes, e.g., absentee, election day, early, etc.
For any/all classes of absentee, generally when absentee is not broken out into specific classes.
A class of absentee; for absentee ballots cast in-person, e.g., at a county office.
A class of absentee; for postal mail absentee ballots separately.
for legislative balance-of-power results information
Total of all ballots cast regardless of voting class.
A class of absentee; for absentee ballots from UOCAVA voters.
Enumerations for vote variations applicable to a contest, e.g., n-of-m, approval, etc.
When voter can select as many candidates as desired in a contest up to a max number.
When voter can allocate more than one vote to a given candidate.
Includes vote for 1, i.e., 1-of-m.
Class/element that is a type of ballot selection specific to selecting a candCodeate in a contest for an office.
Bolean to indicate whether the candidate is a write-in.
Class/element used to treat straight party selection as a type of contest. Used so as to keep a count of straight party selections.
Count of contest votes cast; can include a factional component in special cases.
A number associated with the reporting unit (e.g. a precinct number); for compatibility with VIP.
For reporting unit jurisdictions, number of associated precincts that have completed reporting.
For reporting unit jurisdictions, total number of associated precincts.

Type of reporting unit, e.g., state, jurisdiction, district, etc.
This field is a key into the NIST maintained registry of GpUnit types. The key specifies the geo-political category of the locality, the type of locality, and optionally a sub-type.
If an 'Other' type or subtype is specified, then it will be defined via the OtherType value.
Number of registered voters residing within the boundaries of the reporting unit.
Candidate's last name.
A listing of each line in the contact's postal address that follows the addressee's Name. Name is assumed to be the first line of the address.
The contact's name. This is also the first line of the contact's address.
Restricts time to require inclusion of timezone information and excludes fractional seconds
This association is populated if the BallotStyle is specific to a particular party or parties
If a Coalition is only valid for certain contest(s), they are specified via this association. If no contests are specified, it is assumed that the coalition is valid for all contests.
Restricts dateTime to require inclusion of timezone information and excludes fractional seconds
For defining a reusable set of headers.
For associating an ID with the ballot style.
For the appearance of a header on a particular ballot style

An abstract base class for content that can appear on a particular ballot style.

 

OrderedContent is an abstract class with two subclasses that get used according to the type of content:

  • OrderedHeader, used for the appearance of a contest independent header
  • OrderedContent, used for the appearance of a contest, optionally with the inclusion of contest headers.

A W3C standard data type for a binary floating-point number. The W3C definition of xsd:double is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
The xsd:double is a number where the value can be positive, negative, integer or floating point, with at least 7 digits of precision. Numbers are assumed to be positive but can be explicitly designated as positive by preceding the number with a ‘+’ (ASCII decimal 43) character. Negative numbers must be explicitly designated as negative by a preceding ‘–‘ (ASCII decimal 45) character. An internal representation of an IEEE double precision floating-point number is assumed. This range of values for IEEE doubles is defined as 3.4x10-38 ≤ value ≤ 3.4x10+38. The format for representing a double is the same as the format used in the computer languages C, Perl, Python, or TCL. For example, all the following are legal numbers:
1.005 ; 0.01; .01; -2.334e-33; .224e-2

A W3C standard data type for non-negative integer numbers. The W3C definition of xsd:nonNegativeInteger is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
The range of values allowed are 0 ≤ value ≤ 2147483647 (the non-negative values that fit in a 32 bit signed integer).

The W3C standard data type for the current date and time is xsd:dateTime. (See http://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime-970915.html.) The following formats from the W3C specification are recommended for 258X files:
Complete date plus hours, minutes and seconds:
YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssTZD (e.g. 1997-07-16T19:20:30.4536+01:00)
Complete date plus hours, minutes, seconds and a decimal fraction of a Second:
YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.sTZD (e.g. 1997-07-16T19:20:30.45+01:00)
where:
YYYY = four-digit year
MM = two-digit month (01=January, etc.)
DD = two-digit day of month (01 through 31)
Hh = two digits of hour (00 through 23) (am/pm NOT allowed)
Mm = two digits of minute (00 through 59)
Ss = two digits of second (00 through 59)
S = one or more digits representing a decimal fraction of a second
TZD = time zone designator (Z or +hh:mm or –hh:mm)
A W3C standard data type for a Unicode character string. The characters are from the UTF-8 character set as defined in http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2279.txt.
The data is encoded using base64. (see IETF RFC 1421 for the base64 algorithm and http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/#base64Binary)
A W3C standard data type for hyperlinks. The W3C definition of xsd:anyURI is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.

A W3C standard data type for positive integer numbers. The W3C definition of xsd:positiveInteger is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
The range of values allowed are 1 ≤ value ≤ 2147483647 (the positive values that fit in a 32 bit signed integer).
The W3C standard for an unsigned byte (an unsigned 8 bit integer with a value between 0- 255.) The W3C definition of xsd:unsignedByte is in http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/.
